\par \pard\plain \s17\loch\sl276\slmult1\sb0\sa140\fi0\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar{\hich\af4\loch\cf1\f4\loch
Concordia Central Hub (13th District \u8211\'96 Neutral)\line Expanded DetailSpecific Types of Locations1. The Grand Nexus Plaza\line The massive central square where major public announcements are made. It is surrounded by district embassies and administrative buildings. During crises, it becomes a place of tense gatherings, protests, and urgent public addresses.2. The Unity Spire\line The tallest and most symbolically important building in the Hub. It houses the main governmental offices, the emergency command center, and the highest-level decision-makers. Many floors now contain temporary offices and emergency operations rooms.3. Inter-District Negotiation Halls\line Large, neutral chambers designed for high-stakes talks between districts and factions. These halls are soundproofed, heavily monitored, and often feel like battlegrounds where fragile compromises are forged.4. The Resource Coordination Center\line The high-tech nerve center of the city. Real-time data from all districts flows here. Analysts and coordinators work around the clock to monitor power, heat, siligel, and critical supplies, then make allocation decisions.5. Memorial Hall of the Long Night\line A dignified, somber hall used for official ceremonies, remembrance events, and important state functions. It serves as a reminder of what the city has already survived.6. Emergency Crisis Wing\line A fortified section with independent power, life-support systems, and hardened communications. It is activated during major blackouts or city-wide emergencies.7. Public Petition Atrium\line An open, accessible area where citizens from any district can submit formal petitions, complaints, or requests. It is often crowded and emotionally charged.8. The Scales Bridge\line A grand elevated walkway connecting the main governmental buildings. It is both functional and symbolic, representing the Hub\u8217\'92s role in balancing the city\u8217\'92s competing needs.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\rtlch\afs12 \ltrch\loch\sb0\sa283\brdrt\brdrnone\brdrl\brdrnone\brdrb\brdrdb\brdrw1\brdrcf15\brsp0\brdrr\brdrnone\noline\fs12\ltrpar\loch

\par \pard\plain \s17\loch\sl276\slmult1\sb0\sa140\fi0\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar{\hich\af4\loch\cf1\f4\loch
Notable NPCs (Examples)Councilor Helena Voss\line A senior human administrator known for her calm demeanor and skill at brokering difficult compromises. She is widely respected but increasingly exhausted by the impossible choices forced by the energy crisis. Many see her as one of the last true believers in balanced governance.Unit-42\line A robot resource analyst who works in the Resource Coordination Center. He is precise, logical, and quietly troubled by the moral weight of allocation decisions. He often runs late-night simulations trying to find \u8220\'93fair\u8221\'94 solutions that don\u8217\'92t exist.Theo\line A young human clerk in the Public Petition Atrium. He is idealistic but becoming disillusioned as he processes angry complaints from every district. He represents the younger generation of staff who are burning out quickly.Ambassador Lira Solen\line A skilled human diplomat who specializes in negotiations between the Undergrid, the surface districts, and the Hub itself. She is pragmatic and often acts as a bridge between conflicting sides.Councilor Veyr-3\line A robot politician who advocates for more humanitarian and long-term approaches. He frequently clashes with more pragmatic members who want to prioritize immediate survival, even if it means favoring certain districts.}
\par \pard\plain \s21\rtlch\afs12 \ltrch\loch\sb0\sa283\brdrt\brdrnone\brdrl\brdrnone\brdrb\brdrdb\brdrw1\brdrcf15\brsp0\brdrr\brdrnone\noline\fs12\ltrpar\loch

\par \pard\plain \s17\loch\sl276\slmult1\sb0\sa140\fi0\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\sb0\sa0\ltrpar{\hich\af4\loch\cf1\f4\loch
Daily Life ExamplesExample 1: A Senior Councilor\line Councilor Helena Voss starts her day with emergency briefings about overnight blackouts and district complaints. She spends the morning in back-to-back negotiation sessions trying to mediate between the Thermal Spire and the Hearthward. In the afternoon she addresses public frustration in the Grand Nexus Plaza. In the evening she works late, reviewing allocation maps and wondering how much longer the current system can hold before something breaks.Example 2: A Robot Resource Analyst\line Unit-42 spends his day monitoring live data feeds from all districts and running allocation simulations. He is constantly forced to make decisions that will anger at least one side. In the evening he walks the Scales Bridge alone, quietly processing the growing hostility directed at the Hub from every direction.Example 3: A Young Clerk\line Theo processes citizen petitions in the Public Petition Atrium. He spends much of his day fielding angry complaints from residents of every district. In the evening he meets colleagues in a small caf\u233\'e9 near the plaza to vent about the impossible expectations placed on the Hub and the emotional toll of the work.Example 4: A Bonded Diplomatic Pair\line A human negotiator and her robot partner work together facilitating sensitive talks between the Undergrid and surface districts. They spend their overlapping free time listening to ordinary citizens in the Petition Atrium, then return to their quarters exhausted, trying to find ways to present bad news without triggering riots.}
